  &lt;Comment&gt;
    &lt;Title&gt;Really well organised process&lt;/Title&gt;
    &lt;ScreenName&gt;tis&lt;/ScreenName&gt;
    &lt;CommentText&gt;A lump on my chin was examined and found after a biopsy to be non Hodgins Lymphoma. The diagnostic process took 6 weeks during which time I felt as if I was in a well oiled machine, appointments and feedback were swiftly organised. I received a vast quantity of information and numbers to contact should I have any concerns.  
In the event the lymphoma has been found to be low grade and after hospital based reviews I've been placed on a teleconsultation list, for six monthly follow up.  
I found the whole process of diagnosis and follow up really well organised and swift, just what I needed.  
I hear that part of that well oiled machine may be coming apart as the PET scan department at the Churchill hospital Oxford is to be taken over by a private company and will no longer be based at the Churchill. I do question the wisdom of this and the impact upon the diagnosis of cancers in the Oxford area, why remove a vital part of diagnosis from the NHS?&lt;/CommentText&gt;
